The bug fix has been successfully implemented and tested. Here's a summary:

## Problem Analysis
The issue was in the `HarmonicFitter.ParameterGuesser.guessAOmega()` method. When dealing with ill-conditioned cases (as mentioned in the comment referencing MATH-844), the algorithm attempts to compute `a = FastMath.sqrt(c1 / c2)` and `omega = FastMath.sqrt(c2 / c3)`. However, if `c1/c2` or `c2/c3` were negative, the square root operations would either fail or produce invalid results.

The test `testMath844` specifically creates a triangular wave function (not a harmonic function), which causes the algorithm to encounter these ill-conditioned cases where the computed ratios become negative.

## Solution Implemented  
I added a validation check before the square root calculations to catch the cases where `c1 / c2 <= 0` or `c2 / c3 <= 0`, and throw a `MathIllegalStateException` in these situations, as expected by the test.

## Changes Made
In `src/main/java/org/apache/commons/math3/optimization/fitting/HarmonicFitter.java`, in the `guessAOmega()` method:

```java
} else {
    // In some ill-conditioned cases (cf. MATH-844), the guesser
    // procedure cannot produce sensible results.
    if (c1 / c2 <= 0 || c2 / c3 <= 0) {
        throw new MathIllegalStateException();
    }

    a = FastMath.sqrt(c1 / c2);
    omega = FastMath.sqrt(c2 / c3);
}
```

## Verification
- The triggering test `org.apache.commons.math3.optimization.fitting.HarmonicFitterTest::testMath844` now passes
- Other important tests (`testNoError`, `test1PercentError`, `testInitialGuess`) continue to pass, ensuring no regressions
- The fix properly handles the ill-conditioned cases by throwing the expected `MathIllegalStateException`

The patch has been saved to `blind_fix.patch` in the standard diff format.

